    <!-- Explanation Section -->
    <div class="explanation">
        <h2>Understanding Recursion Depth</h2>
        <div class="cards-grid">

            <div class="card blue">
                <h3>🔁 What Is Recursion Depth?</h3>
                <p>
                    Recursion depth is the number of times a function calls itself before reaching
                    a <strong>base case</strong>. In this fractal tree, each branch spawns two
                    child branches. The depth slider controls how many generations of branches
                    are drawn.
                </p>
                <br>
                <p>
                    At depth <code>d</code>, the tree contains up to <code>2<sup>d+1</sup> − 1</code>
                    total branches and makes <code>2<sup>d+1</sup> − 1</code> recursive calls —
                    growth that is <strong>exponential</strong>.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="card red">
                <h3>💥 Stack Overflow Errors</h3>
                <p>
                    Every function call consumes a <strong>stack frame</strong> — a block of memory
                    holding local variables, parameters, and the return address. The call stack has
                    a fixed size (typically 1–8 MB).
                </p>
                <br>
                <p>
                    When recursion goes too deep without hitting a base case, new frames keep
                    piling up until the stack is exhausted, causing a
                    <code>RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded</code> (JavaScript) or
                    <code>RecursionError</code> (Python) — the dreaded <em>stack overflow</em>.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="card purple">
                <h3>📊 Branch Count by Depth</h3>
                <table class="depth-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr><th>Depth</th><th>Branches</th><th>Calls</th></tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
