                        <tr><td>4</td><td>31</td><td>31</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>255</td><td>255</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>2,047</td><td>2,047</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>12</td><td class="highlight">8,191</td><td class="highlight">8,191</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>20</td><td class="highlight">2,097,151</td><td class="highlight">2,097,151</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>

            <div class="card green">
                <h3>✅ Practical Solutions</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Base case first</strong> — always define a clear stopping condition</li>
                    <li><strong>Tail-call optimization</strong> — rewrite as tail recursion where supported</li>
                    <li><strong>Iterative conversion</strong> — replace recursion with an explicit stack (<code>Array</code>)</li>
                    <li><strong>Memoization</strong> — cache results to avoid redundant deep calls</li>
                    <li><strong>Trampolining</strong> — bounce calls through a loop to flatten the stack</li>
                    <li><strong>Increase stack size</strong> — via runtime flags (e.g., Node.js <code>--stack-size</code>)</li>
                    <li><strong>Depth limiting</strong> — cap recursion depth explicitly, as this demo does at 12</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

        </div>

        <div class="warning-box">
            ⚠️ <strong>Why this demo caps at depth 12:</strong>
            At depth 12 the tree already makes <strong>8,191 recursive calls</strong> and draws
            <strong>4,096 leaf segments</strong>. Beyond ~20–25 levels a binary recursive tree
            would require <em>millions</em> of calls per frame, freezing the browser.
            The safe, practical approach used here is an explicit <strong>depth guard</strong>:
            <code>if (depth === 0) return;</code> — a base case that guarantees the recursion
            always terminates.
        </div>
