      <pre><span class="cm">// Simplified recursive branch function</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">branch</span>(x, y, angle, length, depth) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (depth === <span class="nm">0</span>) <span class="kw">return</span>;           <span class="cm">// base case — stop recursing</span>

  <span class="kw">const</span> x2 = x + length * Math.<span class="fn">cos</span>(angle);
  <span class="kw">const</span> y2 = y - length * Math.<span class="fn">sin</span>(angle);
  <span class="fn">drawLine</span>(x, y, x2, y2);

  <span class="fn">branch</span>(x2, y2, angle - spread, length * ratio, depth - <span class="nm">1</span>); <span class="cm">// left</span>
  <span class="fn">branch</span>(x2, y2, angle + spread, length * ratio, depth - <span class="nm">1</span>); <span class="cm">// right</span>
}</pre>
    </div>

    <!-- 2. Stack overflow -->
    <div class="card danger">
      <h3><span class="icon">💥</span> Why Deep Recursion Causes Stack Overflow</h3>
      <p>
        Every JavaScript engine allocates a finite call stack — typically
        <strong>10 000 – 15 000 frames</strong> in V8 (Node / Chrome) and a
        similar amount in SpiderMonkey (Firefox).  If a recursive function keeps
        calling itself without hitting a base case before the stack is full, the
        engine throws a <code>RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded</code>.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Each frame consumes memory</strong> for local variables, the
          return address, and references to outer scopes (closures).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The stack is not the heap.</strong>  Even if gigabytes of heap
          are free, a fixed-size stack will overflow with enough nesting.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Infinite recursion</strong> (missing or unreachable base case)
          always overflows, regardless of stack size.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Exponential branching</strong> doesn't cause overflow by itself
          — the maximum <em>depth</em> of the call stack matters, not the total
          number of calls.  A depth-12 binary tree needs only 12 frames at once.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <pre><span class="cm">// ❌ Classic infinite recursion — no base case</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">countDown</span>(n) {
  <span class="fn">countDown</span>(n - <span class="nm">1</span>);  <span class="cm">// RangeError after ~10 000 calls</span>
}

<span class="cm">// ❌ Accidental infinite recursion — base case unreachable</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">badFactorial</span>(n) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (n === <span class="nm">0</span>) <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="nm">1</span>;
  <span class="kw">return</span> n * <span class="fn">badFactorial</span>(n + <span class="nm">1</span>);  <span class="cm">// grows forever!</span>
}</pre>
    </div>

    <!-- 3. Practical limits -->
    <div class="card warning">
      <h3><span class="icon">⚠️</span> Practical Depth Limits in Real Projects</h3>
      <p>
        Even before hitting a hard overflow, deep recursion creates
        <strong>performance problems</strong> and makes debugging harder:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Stack-trace noise:</strong> A 5 000-frame stack trace is almost
          impossible to read in a debugger.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Memory pressure:</strong> Each frame holds references that
          prevent garbage collection of intermediate values.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>JIT de-optimisation:</strong> Engines may bail out of optimised
          code paths for very deep call chains.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> Keep recursive algorithms below
          ~1 000 levels of depth for safety.  For deeper problems, switch to an
          iterative approach.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- 4. Solutions -->
    <div class="card success">
      <h3><span class="icon">✅</span> Practical Solutions</h3>

      <p><strong>① Iterative conversion with an explicit stack</strong></p>
      <p>
        Replace the call stack with a plain array used as a stack.  Push work
        items onto it and process them in a loop.  This moves the "stack" from
        the engine's limited call stack to the virtually unlimited heap.
      </p>
      <pre><span class="cm">// ✅ Iterative fractal tree — no recursion limit</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">drawTreeIterative</span>(startX, startY, startAngle, startLen, maxDepth) {
  <span class="kw">const</span> stack = [{ x: startX, y: startY,
                    angle: startAngle, length: startLen, depth: maxDepth }];

  <span class="kw">while</span> (stack.length > <span class="nm">0</span>) {
    <span class="kw">const</span> { x, y, angle, length, depth } = stack.<span class="fn">pop</span>();
    <span class="kw">if</span> (depth === <span class="nm">0</span>) <span class="kw">continue</span>;

    <span class="kw">const</span> x2 = x + length * Math.<span class="fn">cos</span>(angle);
    <span class="kw">const</span> y2 = y - length * Math.<span class="fn">sin</span>(angle);
    <span class="fn">drawLine</span>(x, y, x2, y2);

    stack.<span class="fn">push</span>({ x: x2, y: y2, angle: angle - spread,
                  length: length * ratio, depth: depth - <span class="nm">1</span> });
    stack.<span class="fn">push</span>({ x: x2, y: y2, angle: angle + spread,
                  length: length * ratio, depth: depth - <span class="nm">1</span> });
  }
}</pre>

      <p><strong>② Tail-Call Optimisation (TCO)</strong></p>
      <p>
        A function is <em>tail-recursive</em> when the recursive call is the
        <strong>very last operation</strong> — no pending work remains after it
        returns.  The ES2015 specification mandates TCO in strict mode, allowing
        the engine to <em>reuse</em> the current stack frame instead of pushing a
        new one, making recursion as memory-efficient as a loop.
      </p>
      <pre><span class="cm">// ✅ Tail-recursive accumulator pattern (single-branch example)</span>
<span class="st">"use strict"</span>;
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">factorial</span>(n, acc = <span class="nm">1</span>) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (n <= <span class="nm">1</span>) <span class="kw">return</span> acc;
  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">factorial</span>(n - <span class="nm">1</span>, n * acc);  <span class="cm">// tail call — no work after this</span>
}
<span class="cm">// ⚠️  TCO is only guaranteed in Safari as of 2024.
//     V8 / SpiderMonkey do NOT implement it for binary branches.</span></pre>

      <p><strong>③ Trampolining</strong></p>
      <p>
        A <em>trampoline</em> is a higher-order function that repeatedly calls a
        thunk (a zero-argument function) until a non-function value is returned.
        This simulates TCO in engines that don't support it natively.
      </p>
      <pre><span class="kw">const</span> <span class="fn">trampoline</span> = fn => (...args) => {
  <span class="kw">let</span> result = <span class="fn">fn</span>(...args);
  <span class="kw">while</span> (<span class="kw">typeof</span> result === <span class="st">'function'</span>) result = <span class="fn">result</span>();
  <span class="kw">return</span> result;
};

<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="fn">factorial</span> = <span class="fn">trampoline</span>(<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">f</span>(n, acc = <span class="nm">1</span>) {
  <span class="kw">return</span> n <= <span class="nm">1</span> ? acc : () => <span class="fn">f</span>(n - <span class="nm">1</span>, n * acc);  <span class="cm">// return a thunk</span>
});</pre>

      <p><strong>④ Memoisation &amp; Dynamic Programming</strong></p>
      <p>
        When a recursive algorithm re-computes the same sub-problems (e.g.
        naïve Fibonacci), caching results with a <code>Map</code> or converting
        to bottom-up DP eliminates redundant calls and dramatically reduces depth.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 5. Summary table -->
    <div class="card">
      <h3><span class="icon">📊</span> Quick-Reference: Depth vs. Branch Count</h3>
      <p>For a binary tree where every node spawns two children:</p>
      <pre>Depth │ Max stack frames │ Total branches drawn
──────┼──────────────────┼─────────────────────
  1   │        1         │          1
  2   │        2         │          3
  4   │        4         │         15
  7   │        7         │        127
 10   │       10         │      1 023
 12   │       12         │      4 095
 20   │       20         │  1 048 575   ← rendering bottleneck
 ~14k │    ~14 000       │  ≫ 10^4000   ← call-stack overflow in V8</pre>
      <p>
        Notice that the <strong>stack depth grows linearly</strong> while the
        total work grows <strong>exponentially</strong>.  Overflow is a depth
        problem, not a branch-count problem.
      </p>
    </div>

  </section>

