<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════
     EXPLANATION SECTION
═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="explanation">

  <div class="section-title">Understanding Recursion &amp; Stack Overflow</div>

  <!-- 1 – What is recursion depth? -->
  <div class="card">
    <h3><span class="icon">🔢</span> What Is Recursion Depth?</h3>
    <p>
      Every time a function calls <strong>itself</strong>, the JavaScript engine
      pushes a new <em>stack frame</em> onto the <strong>call stack</strong>—a
      fixed-size region of memory that stores local variables, arguments, and the
      return address. The recursion depth is simply how many of those frames are
      alive at the same moment.
    </p>
    <p>
      For this fractal tree, each node spawns <strong>two</strong> child calls,
      so the total number of branches grows as
      <strong>2<sup>depth</sup> − 1</strong>.
      At depth 12 that is already <strong>8 191 branches</strong> drawn in a
      single traversal—perfectly fine here because the <em>maximum simultaneous
      stack depth</em> is only 12 frames, not 8 191.
    </p>

    <!-- Depth table -->
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Depth</th>
          <th>Total branches (2ⁿ−1)</th>
          <th>Max simultaneous frames</th>
          <th>Risk</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>1</td><td class="td-ok">None</td></tr>
        <tr><td>5</td><td>31</td><td>5</td><td class="td-ok">None</td></tr>
        <tr><td>10</td><td>1 023</td><td>10</td><td class="td-ok">None</td></tr>
        <tr><td>20</td><td>1 048 575</td><td>20</td><td class="td-ok">None</td></tr>
        <tr><td>1 000</td><td>~10<sup>301</sup></td><td>1 000</td><td class="td-warn">Possible in some engines</td></tr>
        <tr><td>10 000</td><td>~10<sup>3010</sup></td><td>10 000</td><td class="td-danger">Stack overflow likely</td></tr>
        <tr><td>100 000+</td><td>astronomical</td><td>100 000+</td><td class="td-danger">Certain stack overflow</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- 2 – Stack overflow explained -->
  <div class="card">
    <h3><span class="icon">💥</span> Why Deep Recursion Causes Stack Overflow</h3>
    <p>
      The call stack has a hard memory ceiling—typically between
      <strong>~6 000 and ~15 000 frames</strong> in V8 (Chrome/Node.js),
      roughly <strong>~5 000</strong> in SpiderMonkey (Firefox), and as low as
      <strong>~500</strong> in some embedded or server-side environments.
      When a recursive function does not reach its base case before hitting
      that ceiling, the engine throws a
      <strong style="color:#ff7b72;">RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded</strong>.
    </p>

    <!-- Simulated stack visualiser -->
    <p>Simulated call stack for a <em>linear</em> recursion at depth 6
       (e.g., <code>countdown(6)</code>):</p>
    <div class="stack-vis" id="stackVis"></div>

    <p>
      Each frame occupies memory for its <strong>local variables</strong>,
      <strong>arguments</strong>, <strong>return address</strong>, and sometimes
      a <strong>saved frame pointer</strong>. A single frame might use
      64–256 bytes; 10 000 frames × 256 bytes = <strong>2.5 MB</strong>—
      easily exhausting a 1–4 MB stack allocation.
    </p>

    <!-- Code example -->
    <pre><code><span class="cm">// Dangerous: linear recursion with no base-case guard</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">infiniteCount</span>(n) {
  <span class="cm">// No base case → infinite recursion → stack overflow</span>
  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">infiniteCount</span>(n <span class="op">+</span> <span class="st">1</span>);
}

<span class="cm">// Safe for this tree: depth is bounded by the slider (max 12)</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(ctx, x, y, len, angle, depth) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (depth <span class="op">===</span> <span class="st">0</span>) <span class="kw">return</span>;          <span class="cm">// ← base case stops recursion</span>
  <span class="cm">// … draw line …</span>
  <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(ctx, x2, y2, len <span class="op">*</span> ratio, angle <span class="op">-</span> spread, depth <span class="op">-</span> <span class="st">1</span>);
  <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(ctx, x2, y2, len <span class="op">*</span> ratio, angle <span class="op">+</span> spread, depth <span class="op">-</span> <span class="st">1</span>);
}</code></pre>
  </div>

  <!-- 3 – Solutions -->
  <div class="section-title" style="margin-top:8px;">Practical Solutions</div>
  <div class="solutions-grid">

    <!-- Iterative + explicit stack -->
    <div class="solution-card">
      <h3>
        <span>📚</span> Iterative Conversion
        <span class="badge badge-green">Most Reliable</span>
      </h3>
      <p>
        Replace the call stack with an <strong>explicit data structure</strong>
        (usually an array used as a stack or queue). Each "frame" becomes a plain
        object pushed onto the array. The loop pops items and processes them—
        <strong>heap memory</strong> is used instead of the call stack, so the
        limit is effectively your available RAM.
      </p>
      <pre style="font-size:0.75rem;"><code><span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">drawTreeIterative</span>(ctx, startX, startY, len, angle, maxDepth) {
  <span class="kw">const</span> stack <span class="op">=</span> [{ startX, startY, len, angle, depth: maxDepth }];
  <span class="kw">while</span> (stack.length <span class="op">></span> <span class="st">0</span>) {
    <span class="kw">const</span> { x, y, len, angle, depth } <span class="op">=</span> stack.<span class="fn">pop</span>();
    <span class="kw">if</span> (depth <span class="op">===</span> <span class="st">0</span>) <span class="kw">continue</span>;
    <span class="cm">// … draw segment …</span>
    stack.<span class="fn">push</span>({ x: x2, y: y2, len: len<span class="op">*</span>r, angle: angle<span class="op">-</span>s, depth: depth<span class="op">-</span><span class="st">1</span> });
    stack.<span class="fn">push</span>({ x: x2, y: y2, len: len<span class="op">*</span>r, angle: angle<span class="op">+</span>s, depth: depth<span class="op">-</span><span class="st">1</span> });
  }
}</code></pre>
    </div>

    <!-- Tail call optimisation -->
    <div class="solution-card">
      <h3>
        <span>🔁</span> Tail Call Optimisation (TCO)
        <span class="badge badge-blue">ES2015 Spec</span>
      </h3>
      <p>
        When a recursive call is the <strong>very last operation</strong> in a
        function (a <em>tail call</em>), a conforming engine can
        <strong>reuse the current stack frame</strong> instead of allocating a
        new one, keeping stack depth constant (O(1)).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Caveat:</strong> As of 2024, only Safari/JavaScriptCore
        implements TCO in strict mode. V8 and SpiderMonkey have not shipped it
        for general use. Binary-branching trees like this one also cannot be
        trivially converted to tail-call form because there are
        <em>two</em> recursive calls per frame.
      </p>
      <pre style="font-size:0.75rem;"><code><span class="st">"use strict"</span>;
<span class="cm">// Tail-recursive factorial (single call – TCO works)</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">factorial</span>(n, acc <span class="op">=</span> <span class="st">1</span>) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (n <span class="op"><=</span> <span class="st">1</span>) <span class="kw">return</span> acc;
  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">factorial</span>(n <span class="op">-</span> <span class="st">1</span>, n <span class="op">*</span> acc); <span class="cm">// ← tail position</span>
}</code></pre>
    </div>

    <!-- Trampolining -->
    <div class="solution-card">
      <h3>
        <span>🎪</span> Trampolining
        <span class="badge badge-purple">Portable TCO</span>
      </h3>
      <p>
        A <strong>trampoline</strong> is a loop that repeatedly calls a function
        as long as it returns another function (a <em>thunk</em>). This emulates
        TCO in any engine without native support. Each "recursive" call just
        returns a closure; the trampoline loop drives execution without growing
        the stack.
      </p>
      <pre style="font-size:0.75rem;"><code><span class="kw">const</span> <span class="fn">trampoline</span> <span class="op">=</span> fn <span class="op">=></span> (...args) <span class="op">=></span> {
  <span class="kw">let</span> result <span class="op">=</span> <span class="fn">fn</span>(...args);
  <span class="kw">while</span> (<span class="kw">typeof</span> result <span class="op">===</span> <span class="st">'function'</span>) result <span class="op">=</span> <span class="fn">result</span>();
  <span class="kw">return</span> result;
};

<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="fn">safeFactorial</span> <span class="op">=</span> <span class="fn">trampoline</span>(
  <span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">fact</span>(n, acc <span class="op">=</span> <span class="st">1</span>) {
    <span class="kw">if</span> (n <span class="op"><=</span> <span class="st">1</span>) <span class="kw">return</span> acc;
    <span class="kw">return</span> () <span class="op">=></span> <span class="fn">fact</span>(n <span class="op">-</span> <span class="st">1</span>, n <span class="op">*</span> acc); <span class="cm">// thunk</span>
  }
);</code></pre>
    </div>

    <!-- Memoisation / depth guard -->
    <div class="solution-card">
      <h3>
        <span>🛡️</span> Depth Guards &amp; Memoisation
        <span class="badge badge-orange">Defensive Coding</span>
      </h3>
      <p>
        Always enforce a <strong>maximum depth</strong> parameter as a base case.
        For expensive computations, combine recursion with a
        <strong>memo cache</strong> (object or <code>Map</code>) to avoid
        redundant sub-calls, reducing both stack pressure and CPU time.
      </p>
      <pre style="font-size:0.75rem;"><code><span class="kw">const</span> memo <span class="op">=</span> <span class="kw">new</span> <span class="fn">Map</span>();

<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">fib</span>(n) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (n <span class="op"><=</span> <span class="st">1</span>) <span class="kw">return</span> n;
  <span class="kw">if</span> (memo.<span class="fn">has</span>(n)) <span class="kw">return</span> memo.<span class="fn">get</span>(n); <span class="cm">// cache hit</span>
  <span class="kw">const</span> result <span class="op">=</span> <span class="fn">fib</span>(n <span class="op">-</span> <span class="st">1</span>) <span class="op">+</span> <span class="fn">fib</span>(n <span class="op">-</span> <span class="st">2</span>);
  memo.<span class="fn">set</span>(n, result);
  <span class="kw">return</span> result;
}
<span class="cm">// fib(50) now runs in O(n) time, O(n) stack</span></code></pre>
    </div>

  </div><!-- /solutions-grid -->

  <!-- 4 – Practical guidelines -->
  <div class="card">
    <h3><span class="icon">✅</span> Practical Guidelines for Safe Recursion</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>1. Always have a base case</strong> — every recursive path must
      eventually terminate. Missing base cases are the #1 cause of accidental
      stack overflow.<br><br>
      <strong>2. Bound your depth</strong> — pass a <code>maxDepth</code>
      argument and decrement it, throwing or returning early when it reaches
      zero.<br><br>
      <strong>3. Prefer iteration for deep linear recursion</strong> — if your
      recursion depth could exceed ~5 000, convert to an explicit stack loop.<br><br>
      <strong>4. Use async chunking for heavy trees</strong> — break large
      recursive work into microtasks with <code>setTimeout(fn, 0)</code> or
      <code>requestAnimationFrame</code> to avoid blocking the main thread.<br><br>
      <strong>5. Profile before optimising</strong> — modern engines handle
      moderate recursion extremely efficiently. Measure first; optimise only
      when you have evidence of a real problem.
    </p>
  </div>

</section>

