<!-- ── Explanation ── -->
<div class="explanation">

  <div class="section-title">📚 Understanding Recursion &amp; Its Limits</div>

  <!-- 1. How the tree works -->
  <div class="card">
    <h3><span class="emoji">🔍</span> How the Fractal Tree Uses Recursion</h3>
    <p>
      Each call to <code>drawBranch(x, y, angle, length, depth)</code> draws one line segment,
      then calls itself <em>twice</em> — once for the left sub-branch and once for the right —
      with a shorter length and adjusted angle. The recursion stops when <code>depth === 0</code>.
    </p>
    <pre><span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(x, y, angle, length, depth) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (depth <span class="op">===</span> <span class="nm">0</span>) <span class="kw">return</span>;          <span class="cm">// base case</span>

  <span class="kw">const</span> x2 <span class="op">=</span> x <span class="op">+</span> Math.<span class="fn">cos</span>(angle) <span class="op">*</span> length;
  <span class="kw">const</span> y2 <span class="op">=</span> y <span class="op">+</span> Math.<span class="fn">sin</span>(angle) <span class="op">*</span> length;

  ctx.<span class="fn">beginPath</span>();
  ctx.<span class="fn">moveTo</span>(x, y);
  ctx.<span class="fn">lineTo</span>(x2, y2);
  ctx.<span class="fn">stroke</span>();

  <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(x2, y2, angle <span class="op">-</span> SPREAD, length <span class="op">*</span> RATIO, depth <span class="op">-</span> <span class="nm">1</span>); <span class="cm">// left</span>
  <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(x2, y2, angle <span class="op">+</span> SPREAD, length <span class="op">*</span> RATIO, depth <span class="op">-</span> <span class="nm">1</span>); <span class="cm">// right</span>
}</pre>
    <p>
      At depth <em>d</em>, the total number of branches is <strong>2<sup>d+1</sup> − 2</strong>.
      Depth 12 produces <strong>8 190</strong> branches — perfectly manageable because the
      call stack only needs to hold one path from root to leaf at a time (depth 12 = 12 frames deep).
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- 2. Call stack visualiser -->
  <div class="card">
    <h3><span class="emoji">📦</span> Live Call-Stack Depth Visualiser</h3>
    <p>Each coloured bar represents one stack frame held in memory along the deepest active path.</p>
    <div class="stack-label">Stack grows upward ↑</div>
    <div class="stack-vis" id="stackVis"></div>
    <p style="margin-top:8px">
      Notice that even at depth 12 the stack is only <strong>12 frames deep</strong>.
      The tree is wide (many branches) but not <em>tall</em> in stack terms — this is why
      binary-tree recursion rarely overflows in practice unless the depth is enormous.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- 3. Why stack overflow happens -->
  <div class="card">
    <h3><span class="emoji">💥</span> Why Deep Recursion Causes Stack Overflow</h3>
    <p>
      Every function call pushes a <em>stack frame</em> onto the call stack. The frame stores
      the return address, local variables, and parameters. JavaScript engines typically allow
      between <strong>10 000 and 15 000</strong> frames before throwing:
    </p>
    <pre><span class="cm">// Naive countdown — blows the stack for large n</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">countdown</span>(n) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (n <span class="op">===</span> <span class="nm">0</span>) <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="st">"done"</span>;
  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">countdown</span>(n <span class="op">-</span> <span class="nm">1</span>);   <span class="cm">// each call waits for the next</span>
}

<span class="fn">countdown</span>(<span class="nm">100000</span>);
<span class="cm">// ❌ RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded</span></pre>
    <ul>
      <li>Each pending call occupies memory until it returns.</li>
      <li>Linear recursion (<code>f(n) → f(n-1)</code>) keeps <em>n</em> frames alive simultaneously.</li>
      <li>The fractal tree only keeps <em>depth</em> frames alive — much safer.</li>
      <li>Stack size is fixed by the engine (V8 ≈ 15 000 frames on 64-bit systems).</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- 4. Practical solutions -->
  <div class="card">
    <h3><span class="emoji">🛠️</span> Practical Solutions</h3>

    <h3 style="color:#7ecfff; font-size:0.9rem; margin-top:4px;">① Iterative Approach (Explicit Stack)</h3>
    <p>Replace the call stack with a manual stack stored in a plain array. Zero risk of overflow.</p>
    <pre><span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">drawTreeIterative</span>(startX, startY, startAngle, startLen, maxDepth) {
  <span class="kw">const</span> stack <span class="op">=</span> [{ x: startX, y: startY,
                    angle: startAngle, len: startLen, depth: maxDepth }];

  <span class="kw">while</span> (stack.length <span class="op">></span> <span class="nm">0</span>) {
    <span class="kw">const</span> { x, y, angle, len, depth } <span class="op">=</span> stack.<span class="fn">pop</span>();
    <span class="kw">if</span> (depth <span class="op">===</span> <span class="nm">0</span>) <span class="kw">continue</span>;

    <span class="kw">const</span> x2 <span class="op">=</span> x <span class="op">+</span> Math.<span class="fn">cos</span>(angle) <span class="op">*</span> len;
    <span class="kw">const</span> y2 <span class="op">=</span> y <span class="op">+</span> Math.<span class="fn">sin</span>(angle) <span class="op">*</span> len;
    <span class="fn">drawLine</span>(x, y, x2, y2);

    stack.<span class="fn">push</span>({ x: x2, y: y2, angle: angle <span class="op">-</span> SPREAD, len: len <span class="op">*</span> RATIO, depth: depth <span class="op">-</span> <span class="nm">1</span> });
    stack.<span class="fn">push</span>({ x: x2, y: y2, angle: angle <span class="op">+</span> SPREAD, len: len <span class="op">*</span> RATIO, depth: depth <span class="op">-</span> <span class="nm">1</span> });
  }
}</pre>

    <h3 style="color:#7ecfff; font-size:0.9rem; margin-top:8px;">② Tail-Call Optimisation (TCO)</h3>
    <p>
      A function is <em>tail-recursive</em> when its recursive call is the very last operation —
      the engine can reuse the current frame instead of pushing a new one, keeping stack depth at O(1).
    </p>
    <pre><span class="cm">// Tail-recursive accumulator pattern</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">sumTo</span>(n, acc <span class="op">=</span> <span class="nm">0</span>) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (n <span class="op">===</span> <span class="nm">0</span>) <span class="kw">return</span> acc;
  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">sumTo</span>(n <span class="op">-</span> <span class="nm">1</span>, acc <span class="op">+</span> n);  <span class="cm">// ← tail position ✅</span>
}
<span class="cm">// ES2015 specifies TCO, but only Safari fully implements it (2024).
// In V8/SpiderMonkey, use the iterative form for safety.</span></pre>

    <h3 style="color:#7ecfff; font-size:0.9rem; margin-top:8px;">③ Trampolining</h3>
    <p>
      A <em>trampoline</em> is a loop that repeatedly calls a function that returns either a value
      or <em>another function to call</em>. It converts deep recursion into a flat loop
      without changing the logical structure much.
    </p>
    <pre><span class="kw">const</span> <span class="fn">trampoline</span> <span class="op">=</span> fn <span class="op">=></span> (...args) <span class="op">=></span> {
  <span class="kw">let</span> result <span class="op">=</span> <span class="fn">fn</span>(...args);
  <span class="kw">while</span> (<span class="kw">typeof</span> result <span class="op">===</span> <span class="st">"function"</span>) result <span class="op">=</span> <span class="fn">result</span>();
  <span class="kw">return</span> result;
};

<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="fn">countdown</span> <span class="op">=</span> <span class="fn">trampoline</span>(
  <span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">step</span>(n) {
    <span class="kw">if</span> (n <span class="op">===</span> <span class="nm">0</span>) <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="st">"done"</span>;
    <span class="kw">return</span> () <span class="op">=></span> <span class="fn">step</span>(n <span class="op">-</span> <span class="nm">1</span>);  <span class="cm">// return thunk, not a call</span>
  }
);

<span class="fn">countdown</span>(<span class="nm">1_000_000</span>); <span class="cm">// ✅ no overflow</span></pre>

    <h3 style="color:#7ecfff; font-size:0.9rem; margin-top:8px;">④ Memoisation &amp; Dynamic Programming</h3>
    <p>
      For problems with overlapping sub-problems (e.g. Fibonacci, shortest paths), cache results
      so each sub-problem is solved only once — reducing both time complexity and the depth of
      the recursion tree.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- 5. Comparison table -->
  <div class="card">
    <h3><span class="emoji">⚖️</span> Approach Comparison</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Approach</th>
          <th>Stack Overflow Risk</th>
