  <!-- WHAT IS RECURSION DEPTH -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2><span class="icon">📐</span> What Recursion Depth Actually Means</h2>
    <p>
      Every time a function calls itself, the JavaScript engine must <strong>suspend the current execution context</strong>
      and push a new <em>stack frame</em> onto the call stack. A stack frame holds everything needed to resume the
      caller later: local variables, the return address, the value of <code>this</code>, function arguments,
      and internal bookkeeping data. None of that can be discarded until the callee returns.
    </p>
    <p>
      For this fractal tree, each call to <code>drawBranch(depth)</code> spawns two child calls:
      <code>drawBranch(depth - 1)</code>. Those each spawn two more. The call stack therefore grows
      <strong>linearly with depth</strong> — at depth 12 the deepest chain is 12 frames tall — but the
      <strong>total number of calls grows as 2<sup>depth+1</sup> − 1</strong>. At depth 12 that is
      8,191 calls. This tree is well-behaved. Real-world unbounded recursion can be far worse.
    </p>

    <div class="stack-diagram">
      <div style="color:#8b949e;font-size:0.75rem;margin-bottom:8px;">CALL STACK — depth 4 example (rightmost branch path)</div>
      <div class="frame overflow"><span>drawBranch(0) ← leaf, returns immediately</span><span class="frame-label">TOP</span></div>
      <div class="frame active"><span>drawBranch(1) — waiting for child</span><span class="frame-label">depth 3</span></div>
      <div class="frame active"><span>drawBranch(2) — waiting for child</span><span class="frame-label">depth 2</span></div>
      <div class="frame active"><span>drawBranch(3) — waiting for child</span><span class="frame-label">depth 1</span></div>
      <div class="frame active"><span>drawBranch(4) — waiting for child</span><span class="frame-label">depth 0</span></div>
      <div class="frame"><span>draw() — initial call</span><span class="frame-label">BOTTOM</span></div>
    </div>

    <p>
      Each frame above is <strong>alive and occupying memory simultaneously</strong>. The engine cannot garbage-collect
      any of them. They are all reachable, waiting. This is the fundamental cost of recursion: memory proportional to
      the maximum depth of the call chain, not just the number of operations.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- WHY STACK OVERFLOW -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2><span class="icon">💥</span> Why Stack Overflows Happen — The Real Mechanics</h2>
    <p>
      JavaScript engines allocate a <strong>fixed-size contiguous memory region</strong> for the call stack.
      This is not the heap. It is a separate, much smaller region — typically between
      <em>500 KB and 2 MB</em> depending on the engine and platform. V8 (Node.js / Chrome) defaults to roughly
      <strong>984 frames</strong> in a typical configuration before throwing
      <code>RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded</code>.
      SpiderMonkey (Firefox) allows around 50,000 — it uses a different stack management strategy.
      JavaScriptCore (Safari) sits somewhere in between.
    </p>
    <p>
      The limit is not measured in frames directly. It is measured in <strong>bytes of stack space consumed</strong>.
      Each frame's size depends on how many local variables it has, the size of those variables, alignment padding,
      and the engine's internal overhead per frame. A function with 20 local <code>float64</code> values uses
      more stack per call than one with a single integer. This is why the exact frame limit varies between functions.
    </p>

    <div class="warning-box">
      ⚠️ <strong>The dangerous pattern:</strong> Recursion over user-supplied data with no depth guard.
      A JSON parser, a tree walker, a file-system traverser — any of these can receive input with
      arbitrarily deep nesting. If your recursion depth is bounded only by the input, a malicious or
      simply large input can crash your program with a stack overflow. This is not a theoretical concern.
      It is a real class of denial-of-service vulnerability.
    </div>

    <p>
      There is also a subtler failure mode: <strong>silent incorrect results</strong>. In some environments,
      stack overflows in worker threads or WebAssembly can produce undefined behavior rather than a clean
      exception. You cannot always rely on catching the error.
    </p>

    <pre><span class="cm">// This looks innocent. It is not.</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">sumArray</span>(<span class="param">arr</span>, <span class="param">index</span> = <span class="num">0</span>) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (index >= arr.length) <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="num">0</span>;
  <span class="kw">return</span> arr[index] + <span class="fn">sumArray</span>(arr, index + <span class="num">1</span>); <span class="cm">// NOT tail position</span>
}

<span class="cm">// sumArray(new Array(100000)) → RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded
// The addition happens AFTER the recursive call returns.
// The frame cannot be reused. 100,000 frames pile up.</span></pre>
  </div>

  <!-- THE CODE -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2><span class="icon">🌲</span> How This Tree Is Drawn</h2>
    <p>
      The fractal uses a classic recursive branch algorithm. Each call draws one line segment, then
      rotates the canvas context and calls itself twice with a reduced length and depth.
      The canvas transform stack mirrors the call stack — <code>save()</code> and <code>restore()</code>
      bracket each frame, which is why this approach is clean to write but still consumes stack frames.
    </p>
    <pre><span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(<span class="param">ctx</span>, <span class="param">len</span>, <span class="param">depth</span>, <span class="param">maxDepth</span>) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (depth === <span class="num">0</span>) <span class="kw">return</span>; <span class="cm">// base case — stop recursing</span>

  <span class="cm">// Hue shifts from brown (trunk) to green (leaves)</span>
