<h1>Fractal Tree — Recursion Depth Explorer</h1>

<div id="canvas-wrapper">
  <canvas id="tree-canvas"></canvas>
</div>

<div class="controls">
  <label for="depth-slider">Depth</label>
  <input type="range" id="depth-slider" min="1" max="12" value="7">
  <span id="depth-display">7</span>
  <div class="stats">
    Branches: <span id="branch-count">—</span> &nbsp;|&nbsp;
    Draw: <span id="draw-time">—</span>ms
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─── EXPLAINER ─────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<div class="explainer">

  <section>
    <h2>What recursion depth actually means</h2>
    <p>
      Every time a function calls itself, the CPU needs somewhere to store that
      call's local state — its arguments, local variables, return address, and
      saved registers. That somewhere is the <strong>call stack</strong>, a
      fixed-size block of memory (typically <strong>1–8 MB</strong> per thread,
      set by the OS or runtime at process start). Each layer of recursion
      consumes one <em>stack frame</em>. For this tree, each frame holds the
      branch position, angle, length, and the current depth counter.
    </p>
    <p>
      At depth 12 this tree spawns <strong>2<sup>12</sup> − 1 = 4,095</strong>
      branches via 4,095 recursive calls, but because the recursion is
      depth-first, <em>at most 12 frames are alive simultaneously</em> — one
      per level of the call stack. That is why depth 12 works fine here.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why stack overflow actually happens</h2>
    <p>
      Stack overflow is not about <em>total</em> calls made. It is about
      <em>simultaneous</em> live frames. The stack grows with each nested call
      and shrinks as calls return. Overflow happens when the stack pointer
      crosses the guard page the OS placed at the stack's boundary. The OS
      raises a hardware exception (<code>SIGSEGV</code> on Linux,
      <code>EXCEPTION_STACK_OVERFLOW</code> on Windows) which the runtime
      converts into a language-level error.
    </p>
    <div class="stack-diagram">
      <div style="color:#8b949e;font-size:0.75rem;margin-bottom:8px;">
        ▼ Stack grows downward in memory
      </div>
      <div class="frame active">
        <span class="frame-label">frame 0</span>
        <span class="frame-content">drawBranch(depth=0, x, y, angle, len)</span>
        <span class="frame-size">~128 B</span>
      </div>
      <div class="frame active">
        <span class="frame-label">frame 1</span>
        <span class="frame-content">drawBranch(depth=1, …)</span>
        <span class="frame-size">~128 B</span>
      </div>
      <div class="frame active">
        <span class="frame-label">frame 2</span>
        <span class="frame-content">drawBranch(depth=2, …)</span>
        <span class="frame-size">~128 B</span>
      </div>
      <div class="frame warn">
        <span class="frame-label">frame N</span>
        <span class="frame-content">drawBranch(depth=N, …)  ← still recursing</span>
        <span class="frame-size">~128 B</span>
      </div>
      <div class="frame danger">
        <span class="frame-label">frame N+1</span>
        <span class="frame-content">drawBranch(depth=N+1, …) ← stack full</span>
        <span class="frame-size">~128 B</span>
      </div>
      <div class="overflow-line">
        ⚠ Stack boundary — next write hits the guard page → RangeError / StackOverflowError
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      In JavaScript the typical limit is roughly <strong>10,000–15,000</strong>
      frames (V8), but it varies by engine, OS, and frame size. In Python it is
      deliberately capped at <strong>1,000</strong> by default
      (<code>sys.setrecursionlimit</code>) as a safety valve, not a hardware
      limit. In languages without TCO, infinite mutual recursion will always
      overflow eventually regardless of that cap.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The real causes — not just "too many calls"</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Missing or wrong base case.</strong> The most common bug.
        The recursion never bottoms out, so frames accumulate without bound.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Large frame size.</strong> A recursive function that allocates a
        large local array or struct per call exhausts the stack far sooner than
        one with only a few scalars. Frame size multiplied by depth equals stack
        consumed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Unbounded input depth.</strong> Parsing deeply nested JSON,
        traversing a degenerate binary tree (effectively a linked list), or
        walking a graph with a long chain — the recursion depth is driven by
        data you don't control.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Mutual recursion hiding depth.</strong>
        <code>A→B→C→A→B→C…</code> Each hop adds a frame. The cycle is
        invisible if you only look at one function.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Threads with small stack sizes.</strong> Worker threads are
        often given 256 KB or less. Recursive code that works on the main
        thread crashes on a worker.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Real solutions — with honest trade-offs</h2>
    <div class="solution-grid">

      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>1. Explicit stack (heap-allocated) <span class="tag tag-best">Best general fix</span></h3>
        <p>
          Replace the call stack with your own stack data structure on the heap.
          Push work items instead of making recursive calls. The heap is orders
          of magnitude larger than the stack (gigabytes vs. megabytes).
          Iterative DFS/BFS over trees and graphs uses this pattern.
          Trade-off: code is less readable; you must manually manage the
          work-item structure.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>2. Tail-call optimisation (TCO) <span class="tag tag-lang">Language-dependent</span></h3>
        <p>
          When a recursive call is the <em>very last</em> thing a function does,
          a compiler can reuse the current frame instead of allocating a new one,
          making recursion O(1) in stack space. Scheme guarantees TCO.
          Haskell's laziness achieves similar results. JavaScript's spec
          requires it in strict mode but only Safari implements it. Python and
          Java deliberately omit it. Do not rely on TCO unless your language
          explicitly guarantees it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>3. Trampolining <span class="tag tag-simple">Works anywhere</span></h3>
        <p>
          Instead of calling itself, a function returns a <em>thunk</em> — a
          zero-argument closure representing the next step. A top-level loop
          (the trampoline) calls thunks until one returns a plain value.
          Stack depth stays at 2 regardless of logical recursion depth.
          Works in any language with first-class functions. Trade-off:
          allocates a closure object per step on the heap.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>4. Increase the stack size <span class="tag tag-simple">Quick, limited</span></h3>
        <p>
          On threads you create, you can specify a larger stack
          (<code>pthread_attr_setstacksize</code>, Java's
          <code>new Thread(r, name, stackSize)</code>,
          Rust's <code>Builder::stack_size</code>).
          In Python, <code>sys.setrecursionlimit</code> raises the frame cap but
          the underlying OS stack must be large enough too.
          This is a band-aid — it delays the problem, it does not eliminate it.
          Never use it as the only fix for unbounded recursion.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>5. Continuation-passing style (CPS)</h3>
        <p>
          Transform the recursive algorithm so that instead of returning a value
          up the call chain, each step receives a callback (continuation)
          representing "what to do next." Combined with trampolining, this
          eliminates stack growth entirely. This is how async/await is
          desugared by compilers under the hood. Trade-off: significant
          cognitive overhead; error handling becomes complex.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>6. Memoisation + dynamic programming</h3>
        <p>
          For problems with overlapping subproblems (Fibonacci, edit distance,
          shortest paths), convert top-down recursion to bottom-up iteration.
          You eliminate both stack overflow risk and redundant recomputation.
          This is not universally applicable — it requires optimal substructure
          — but when it applies it is the best solution on every axis.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why this tree visualisation does not overflow at depth 12</h2>
    <p>
      The implementation below uses a straightforward recursive approach because
      the maximum depth is bounded to 12 by the UI slider. At depth 12, the
      maximum simultaneous call stack depth is exactly 13 frames (trunk + 12
      levels). Each frame is tiny — a handful of numbers. The total stack
      consumed is well under 10 KB. The exponential growth you see visually
      (4,095 branches) is in <em>total work</em>, not in <em>stack depth</em>.
      This is a critical distinction: a balanced binary tree of depth N has
      2<sup>N</sup>−1 nodes but requires only N frames of stack at any moment.
    </p>
  </section>

</div>

<script>
(function () {
  'use strict';

  const canvas  = document.getElementById('tree-canvas');
  const ctx     = canvas.getContext('2d');
  const slider  = document.getElementById('depth-slider');
  const depthEl = document.getElementById('depth-display');
  const countEl = document.getElementById('branch-count');
  const timeEl  = document.getElementById('draw-time');

  // ── Sizing ────────────────────────────────────────────────
  function resize() {
    const maxW = Math.min(window.innerWidth - 32, 700);
    const h    = Math.round(maxW * 0.72);
    canvas.width  = maxW;
    canvas.height = h;
    draw();
  }

  // ── Colour mapping by depth ───────────────────────────────
  // Trunk is warm brown; tips are cool blue-green.
  function branchColor(depth, maxDepth) {
    const t = depth / maxDepth;
    // Interpolate HSL: 30° (warm brown) → 150° (green) → 200° (blue-green)
    const hue = 30 + t * 170;
    const sat = 60 + t * 20;
    const lit = 35 + t * 30;
    const alpha = 1 - t * 0.3;
    return `hsla(${hue},${sat}%,${lit}%,${alpha})`;
  }

  // ── Recursive draw ────────────────────────────────────────
  let branchCount = 0;

  function drawBranch(x1, y1, angle, length, depth, maxDepth) {
    if (depth > maxDepth) return;

    branchCount++;

    const x2 = x1 + Math.cos(angle) * length;
    const y2 = y1 + Math.sin(angle) * length;

    // Line width tapers from trunk to tip
    const t = depth / maxDepth;
    ctx.lineWidth = Math.max(0.5, (1 - t) * 8 + 0.5);
    ctx.strokeStyle = branchColor(depth, maxDepth);

    ctx.beginPath();
    ctx.moveTo(x1, y1);
    ctx.lineTo(x2, y2);
    ctx.stroke();

    // Draw a small circle at tips for visual polish
    if (depth === maxDepth) {
      ctx.beginPath();
      ctx.arc(x2, y2, 1.5, 0, Math.PI * 2);
      ctx.fillStyle = `hsla(160,80%,70%,0.8)`;
      ctx.fill();
      return;
    }

    const spread    = Math.PI / 5;          // 36° between branches
    const shrink    = 0.68;                 // length multiplier per level
    const nextLen   = length * shrink;
    const wobble    = (depth % 2 === 0 ? 0.04 : -0.04); // subtle asymmetry

    drawBranch(x2, y2, angle - spread + wobble, nextLen, depth + 1, maxDepth);
    drawBranch(x2, y2, angle + spread + wobble, nextLen, depth + 1, maxDepth);
  }

  // ── Main draw entry ───────────────────────────────────────
  function draw() {
    const maxDepth = parseInt(slider.value, 10);
    depthEl.textContent = maxDepth;

    ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

    // Subtle radial gradient background
    const grad = ctx.createRadialGradient(
      canvas.width / 2, canvas.height, 10,
      canvas.width / 2, canvas.height / 2, canvas.height
    );
    grad.addColorStop(0, '#111820');
    grad.addColorStop(1, '#0d1117');
    ctx.fillStyle = grad;
    ctx.fillRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

    branchCount = 0;
    const startX  = canvas.width / 2;
    const startY  = canvas.height - 10;
    const trunkLen = canvas.height * 0.22;

    const t0 = performance.now();
    drawBranch(startX, startY, -Math.PI / 2, trunkLen, 0, maxDepth);
    const t1 = performance.now();

    countEl.textContent = branchCount.toLocaleString();
    timeEl.textContent  = (t1 - t0).toFixed(2);
  }

  // ── Events ────────────────────────────────────────────────
  slider.addEventListener('input', draw);
  window.addEventListener('resize', resize);
  resize();

})();
</script>
</body>
</html>
```

---

## What makes this explanation different from the shallow versions

Most explanations say *"recursion has a limit, don't go too deep."* That is useless. Here is what actually matters:

**The limit is on simultaneous live frames, not total calls.** This tree makes 4,095 calls at depth 12 but only ever has 13 frames alive at once. A naive Fibonacci implementation at `fib(40)` makes 330 million calls but also only has 40 frames alive at once — it won't overflow, it will just be slow.

**Frame size is half the equation.** A recursive function that allocates a 10 KB local buffer per call will overflow at depth 500. A function with five integers per frame can go to depth 50,000 before hitting the wall. Stack overflow = depth × frame size > stack limit.

**The solutions are ranked honestly.** Increasing `sys.setrecursionlimit` is not a fix, it is a delay. An explicit heap stack is the correct general solution. TCO is the elegant solution but you cannot rely on it unless your language guarantees it. Trampolining works everywhere and costs only heap allocations.

